ard University Press |year=1998 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QUkaVq_GlJUC&pg=PA222#v=onepage&q=%22Ham%20laughed%22&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9780674791510 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Levenson |first=Jon D. |editor1-last=Berlin |editor1-first=Adele |editor2-last=Brettler |editor2-first=Marc Zvi |title=The Jewish study Bible |chapter=Genesis: Introduction and Annotations |year=2004 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195297515/page/26 26] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-529751-5 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aDuy3p5QvEYC#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195297515/page/26 }} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=aDuy3p5QvEYC&pg=PR5#v=snippet&q=Levenson&f=false Levenson author note]).\n*{{cite book |last=Lulat |first=G |title=A History of African Higher Education from Antiquity to the Present: A Critical Synthesis. |year=2005 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |isbn=9780313068669 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J00xEkY-vTEC&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=misnomer%20ham&f=false |pages=85, 86 |ref=harv |quote=an ideologically driven misnomer...}}\n*{{cite book |last=Metcalf |first=Alida C. |title=Go-betweens and the Colonization of Brazil, 1500\u20131600 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lWuNIISvBqIC#v=snippet&q=ham%20curse&f=false |year=2005 |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin |isbn=978-0292712768 |edition=1st |page=164 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Reeve|first1=W. Paul|title=Religion of a Different Color: Race and the Mormon Struggle for Whiteness|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95j4BQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-19-975407-6}}\n*{{cite book |last=Robertson |first=John M. |authorlink= |title=Christianity and Mythology |year=1910 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing (2004 reprint) |location= |isbn=978-0-7661-8768-9 |pages=496 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=usGxKc9gMNwC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sadler |first=R.S. |authorlink= |title=Can a Cushite Change his Skin? |year=2005 |publisher=T&T Clark |location= |language= |isbn= 9780567029607|pages=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jNwI0AlRhuwC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sarna |first=Nahum |authorlink=Nahum Sarna |editor-last=Friedman |editor-first=Richard Elliott |title=The Creation of Sacred Literature: Composition and Redaction of the Biblical Text |chapter=The Anticipatory Use of Information as a Literary Feature of the Genesis Narratives |year=1981 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-09637-0 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HvjNTNWTyQUC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/creationofsacred0000unse }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Trost |first=Travis D. |title=Who should be king in Israel? |publisher=Peter Lang Publishing |year=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FnvbpnRwxeYC&pg=PR6#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9781433111518 }}\n*{{cite book |last=VanderKam |first=James Claire |authorlink=James VanderKam |chapter=The Righteousness of Noah |editor=John Joseph Collins |editor2=George W. E. Nickelsburg |title=Ideal figures in ancient Judaism: profiles and paradigms, Volumes 12\u201315 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Le4QAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=1 December 2013 |year=1980 |publisher=Scholars Press |location=Chico |isbn=978-0891304340 |pages=13\u201332|ref=harv}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150309230136/http://www3.nd.edu/~jvanderk/ VanderKam-Vitae]\n*{{cite book |last=Van Seters |first=John |editor1-last=VanderKam |editor1-first=James |title=From Revelation to Canon: Studies in the Hebrew Bible and Second Temple Literature |chapter=Geography as an evaluative tool |year=2000 |pages=|publisher=Brill |isbn= |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L352z_jZSmcC&pg=PA476#v=onepage&q=Putting%20them%20in%20their%20place%3A%20Geography%20as%20an%20evaluative%20tool&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Whitford |first=David M. |title=The curse of Ham in the Early Modern Era |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMb7_SL-OJYC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9780754666257 }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Noah (Biblical figure)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11571-noah \"Noah\"] from the 1901\u20131906 ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]''\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11088a.htm \"Noah\"]\u2014''[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090711130618/http://muslimwiki.com/mw/index.php/Nuh \"Nuh\"]\u2014MuslimWiki\n\n{{Prophets of the Tanakh}}\n{{Adam to David}}\n{{Prophets in the Qur'an|no}}\n{{Noah's Ark}}\n{{Creationism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Noah| ]]\n[[Category:Bereshit (parsha)]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the Old Testament]]\n[[Category:Legendary progenitors]]\n[[Category:Longevity myths]]\n[[Category:Noach (parsha)| ]]\n[[Category:People celebrated in the Lutheran liturgical calendar]]\n[[Category:Book of Genesis people]]\n", "name_user": "Noah950", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noah"}
{"title_page": "Bim Adewunmi", "text_new": "{{short description|British writer and journalist}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Bim Adewunmi\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Writer, producer, journalist \n| language         = English\n| residence        = New York, New York\n| nationality      = British Nigerian\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''[[Thirst Aid Kit]]''\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Bim Adewunmi''' is a British writer and journalist. Adewunmi previously worked as a culture writer at ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]''. She co-hosts the podcast ''[[Thirst Aid Kit]]'' with writer Nichole Perkins. Her debut play, ''Hoard'', premiered at [[Arcola Theatre]] in May 2019. Adewunmi is a producer for ''[[This American Life]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2019/04/what-does-luminarys-very-bad-week-tell-us-about-podcasters-collective-power/|title=What does Luminary's very bad week tell us about podcasters' collective power?|website=Nieman Lab|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/bim-adewunmi-east-london-dalston-a4143076.html|title=Bim Adewunmi recalls the east London that shaped her|date=2019-05-15|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/06/thirst-aid-kit-examines-celebrity-lust.html&usg=AOvVaw0-HCi4DpU-GG5o1BN5le1-|title=Lusting Out Loud|last=Kang|first=Inkoo|date=|website=www.google.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n== Life & career ==\nAdewunmi was born and raised in [[Stratford, London|Stratford]], [[East London]] to Nigerian immigrant parents who are of [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] descent.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2014, she began writing an opinion and culture column in the Lifestyle section of ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/oct/20/thank-you-and-goodbye-readers-you-helped-make-my-dream-come-true|title=Thank you and goodbye, readers: you helped make my dream come true {{!}} Bim Adewunmi|last=Adewunmi|first=Bim|date=2018-10-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She became a culture editor for [[BuzzFeed]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/arts/television/whats-on-tv-thursday-follow-this-on-netflix-and-the-season-finale-of-american-woman.html|title=What's on TV Thursday: 'Follow This' on Netflix and the Season Finale of 'American Woman'|last=McAleavy|first=Emma L.|date=2018-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In November 2017, Adewunmi developed and began cohosting ''[[Thirst Aid Kit]]'', a podcast about celebrity lust, with writer Nichole Perkins. BuzzFeed ended its relationship with the podcast in December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Want to Try Bim Adewunmi and Nichole Perkins's Thirst Aid Kit? Start Here |author=Becca James|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/best-episode-thirst-aid-kit-chris-evans.html|website=Vulture |access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> The podcast was picked up by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' in August 2019, and it will return on September 26, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/entertainment/nichole-perkins-bim-adewunmi-thirst-aid-kit-joining-slate/|title=Exclusive: Nichole Perkins And Bim Adewunmi's 'Thirst Aid Kit' Is Joining Slate|website=Essence|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> She left ''The Guardian'' in October 2018<ref name=\":0\" /> and joined the American public radio program ''[[This American Life]]'' as a producer in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bimadew/status/1122905057215832066?lang=en|title=~some personal news~ today is my first day as a producer with This American Life. So, uh, feel free to hit me up with stories etc. pic.twitter.com/032muBCZS2|last=Adewunmi|first=Bim|date=2019-04-29|website=@bimadew|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\nAdewunmi's debut play, ''Hoard'', premiered at the [[Arcola Theatre]] in May 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /> The play centers on a Nigerian-British family, the Bakares, who reside in East London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/on-stage/hoard-arcola-theatre-review|title=Hoard Puts A New Spin On Meeting The Parents At Arcola Theatre|date=2019-05-24|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/theatre/hoard-review|title=Hoard review: Bim Adewunmi's flawed but lovable debut drama about a British-Nigerian family living in east London|website=Time Out London|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The play received mixed critical reviews. Arifa Akbar wrote in a review for ''The Guardian'', \"...but the hoarding theme ends up feeling confected and simply not dramatic enough to warrant the emotional ruptures it creates\" and gave the show three out of five stars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/may/22/hoard-review-bim-adewunmi-arcola|title=Hoard review \u2013 emotional wreckage from a drive-by family visit|last=Akbar|first=Arifa|date=2019-05-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out London]]'', Rosemary Waugh rated the play three out of five stars and wrote, \"Adewunmi describes her play as \u2018a love letter to east London\u2019, and it shows. It's also a love letter to the characters who are all so warm and lovingly sketched it would be hard to genuinely begrudge spending time in their company.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://twitter.com/bimadew Bim Adewunmi] on Twitter\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adewunmi, Bim}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nigerian women writers]]\n[[Category:English women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:British podcasters]]\n[[Category:British radio producers]]\n[[Category:English people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British writer and journalist}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Bim Adewunmi\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Writer, producer, journalist \n| language         = English\n| residence        = New York, New York\n| nationality      = British Nigerian\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''[[Thirst Aid Kit]]''\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Bim Adewunmi''' is a British writer and journalist. Adewunmi previously worked as a culture writer at ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]''. She co-hosts the podcast ''[[Thirst Aid Kit]]'' with writer Nichole Perkins. Her debut play, ''Hoard'', premiered at [[Arcola Theatre]] in May 2019. Adewunmi is a producer for ''[[This American Life]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2019/04/what-does-luminarys-very-bad-week-tell-us-about-podcasters-collective-power/|title=What does Luminary's very bad week tell us about podcasters' collective power?|website=Nieman Lab|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/bim-adewunmi-east-london-dalston-a4143076.html|title=Bim Adewunmi recalls the east London that shaped her|date=2019-05-15|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/06/thirst-aid-kit-examines-celebrity-lust.html&usg=AOvVaw0-HCi4DpU-GG5o1BN5le1-|title=Lusting Out Loud|last=Kang|first=Inkoo|date=|website=www.google.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\n== Life & career ==\nAdewunmi was born and raised in [[Stratford, London|Stratford]], [[East London]] to Nigerian immigrant parents who are of [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] descent.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2014, she began writing an opinion and culture column in the Lifestyle section of ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/oct/20/thank-you-and-goodbye-readers-you-helped-make-my-dream-come-true|title=Thank you and goodbye, readers: you helped make my dream come true {{!}} Bim Adewunmi|last=Adewunmi|first=Bim|date=2018-10-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She became a culture editor for [[BuzzFeed]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/arts/television/whats-on-tv-thursday-follow-this-on-netflix-and-the-season-finale-of-american-woman.html|title=What's on TV Thursday: 'Follow This' on Netflix and the Season Finale of 'American Woman'|last=McAleavy|first=Emma L.|date=2018-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In November 2017, Adewunmi developed and began cohosting ''[[Thirst Aid Kit]]'', a podcast about celebrity lust, with writer Nichole Perkins. BuzzFeed ended its relationship with the podcast in December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Want to Try Bim Adewunmi and Nichole Perkins's Thirst Aid Kit? Start Here |author=Becca James|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/best-episode-thirst-aid-kit-chris-evans.html|website=Vulture |access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> The podcast was picked up by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' in August 2019, and it will return on September 26, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/entertainment/nichole-perkins-bim-adewunmi-thirst-aid-kit-joining-slate/|title=Exclusive: Nichole Perkins And Bim Adewunmi's 'Thirst Aid Kit' Is Joining Slate|website=Essence|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> She left ''The Guardian'' in October 2018<ref name=\":0\" /> and joined the American public radio program ''[[This American Life]]'' as a producer in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bimadew/status/1122905057215832066?lang=en|title=~some personal news~ today is my first day as a producer with This American Life. So, uh, feel free to hit me up with stories etc. pic.twitter.com/032muBCZS2|last=Adewunmi|first=Bim|date=2019-04-29|website=@bimadew|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\nAdewunmi's debut play, ''Hoard'', premiered at the [[Arcola Theatre]] in May 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /> The play centers on a Nigerian-British family, the Bakares, who reside in East London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/on-stage/hoard-arcola-theatre-review|title=Hoard Puts A New Spin On Meeting The Parents At Arcola Theatre|date=2019-05-24|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/theatre/hoard-review|title=Hoard review: Bim Adewunmi's flawed but lovable debut drama about a British-Nigerian family living in east London|website=Time Out London|language=en|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> The play received mixed critical reviews. Arifa Akbar wrote in a review for ''The Guardian'', \"...but the hoarding theme ends up feeling confected and simply not dramatic enough to warrant the emotional ruptures it creates\" and gave the show three out of five stars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/may/22/hoard-review-bim-adewunmi-arcola|title=Hoard review \u2013 emotional wreckage from a drive-by family visit|last=Akbar|first=Arifa|date=2019-05-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out London]]'', Rosemary Waugh rated the play three out of five stars and wrote, \"Adewunmi describes her play as \u2018a love letter to east London\u2019, and it shows. It's also a love letter to the characters who are all so warm and lovingly sketched it would be hard to genuinely begrudge spending time in their company.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://twitter.com/bimadew Bim Adewunmi] on Twitter\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adewunmi, Bim}}\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nigerian women writers]]\n[[Category:English women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:British podcasters]]\n[[Category:British radio producers]]\n[[Category:English people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bim_Adewunmi"}
{"title_page": "Brighton City Airport", "text_new": "{{confused|Brighton Airport}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox airport \n| name         = Brighton City Airport\n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image        = Brighton_City_Airport_Logo.png\n| image2       = Terminal Building at Shoreham Airport - geograph.org.uk - 573952.jpg\n| image-width  = 150\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA         = ESH\n| ICAO         = EGKA\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = \n| operator     = Brighton City Airport Ltd\n| city-served  = [[South East England|South East]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| location     = [[Lancing, West Sussex|Lancing]], [[West Sussex]]\n| elevation-f  = 7\n| elevation-m  = 2\n| coordinates  = {{coord|50|50|08|N|000|17|50|W|type:airport_region:GB-WSX|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = West Sussex\n| pushpin_label          = EGKA\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in West Sussex\n| website      = [http://www.flybrighton.com/ flybrighton.com]\n| metric-rwy   = Yes\n| r1-number    = 02/20\n| r1-length-f  = 3,399\n| r1-length-m  = 1,036\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number    = 06/24\n| r2-length-f  = 2,621\n| r2-length-m  = 799\n| r2-surface   = [[Grass]]\n| r3-number    = 13/31\n| r3-length-f  = 1,339\n| r3-length-m  = 408\n| r3-surface   = Grass\n| r4-number    = 02/20<BR><small>Unlicensed</small>\n| r4-length-f  = 2,297\n| r4-length-m  = 700\n| r4-surface   = [[Grass]]\n| stat-year    = 2018 \n| stat1-header = Passengers \n| stat1-data   = \u2013\n| stat2-header = Movements\n| stat2-data   = 39,224\n| footnotes    = Sources: UK [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] at [[National Air Traffic Services|NATS]]<ref name=\"aip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nats-uk.ead-it.com/public/index.php%3Foption=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=134&Itemid=183.html|title=NATS \u2013 AIS \u2013 Home|work=ead-it.com}}</ref> <br> Statistics from the [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|UK Civil Aviation Authority]]<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.caa.co.uk/Data-and-analysis/UK-aviation-market/Airports/Datasets/UK-Airport-data/Airport-data-2018/|title=Data and analysis \u2013 UK Civil Aviation Authority|website=www.caa.co.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100618/http://www.caa.co.uk/default.aspx?catid=80&pagetype=88&sglid=3&fld=2014Annual|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref>}}\n\n'''Brighton City Airport''' {{Airport codes|ESH|EGKA}}, also commonly known as '''Shoreham Airport''', is located in the [[Civil parish|parish]] of [[Lancing, West Sussex|Lancing]] in [[West Sussex]], England. It has a [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]] Public Use Aerodrome Licence that allows flights for the public transport of passengers or for flying instruction.\n\nFounded in 1910, it is the oldest airport in the UK and the oldest purpose-built commercial airport in the world.<ref name=\"Bloom 70\">Bloom, Nick. \"Sunny Shoreham\", ''Pilot'', February 2012, p70</ref> It is now owned by Brighton City Airport Ltd (BCAL).<ref name=\"worthingherald.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worthingherald.co.uk/news/local/new-plan-safeguards-future-of-shoreham-airport-1-6035934|title=New plan 'safeguards future of Shoreham Airport'|work=worthingherald.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502215824/http://www.worthingherald.co.uk/news/local/new-plan-safeguards-future-of-shoreham-airport-1-6035934|archivedate=2 May 2014}}</ref> The 1930s [[Art Deco]] terminal building designed by [[R Stavers Hessell Tiltman]] is [[listed building|listed]] grade II*.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=1353731&resourceID=5|title=Heritage Gateway \u2013 Results|website=www.heritagegateway.org.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813221550/http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=1353731&resourceID=5|archivedate=13 August 2017}}</ref> The airport is {{Convert|1|NM|abbr=on|lk=in}} west of [[Shoreham-by-Sea]]<ref name=\"aip\"/> at [[Lancing, West Sussex|Lancing]] in the [[Adur (district)|Adur]] district of West Sussex. It is situated immediately to the south of the [[A27 road]], between [[Brighton]] and [[Worthing]], and immediately to the north of the [[West Coastway Line|West Coastway]] railway line.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shoreham (Brighton City) Airport (6659107193).jpg|thumb|Interior of the terminal building]]\n[[File:shorehamrunway.jpg|thumb|View of Runway 02 from the [[West Coastway Line|West Coastway]] railway line]]\n\n===Foundation===\nThe first aviator to fly there was [[Harold H. Piffard]] in 1910; a memorial garden celebrates his flight.<ref name=\"Bloom 70\" /> The aerodrome was officially opened on 20 June 1911. The [[Cecil Pashley|first flying school]] opened in 1913.\n\n===First World War===\nDuring the [[World War I|First World War]] the aerodrome was used by the [[Royal Flying Corps]]. It was the departure point for some of the earlier flights, using [[Bl\u00e9riot XI|Bl\u00e9riot]]s<ref>Royal Flying Corps WW1 Bl\u00e9riot XI reconnaissance monoplane | {{cite web |url=http://aircraft-photographs.s3-website-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/aircraft-ww1-RFC-bleriot-XI-observation-monoplane.html |title=Archived Document |accessdate=21 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221052735/http://aircraft-photographs.s3-website-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/aircraft-ww1-RFC-bleriot-XI-observation-monoplane.html |archivedate=21 February 2015  }}</ref> and [[Royal Aircraft Factory B.E.2|BE]]s, to join the conflict across the [[English Channel|Channel]].<ref>Bloom, Nick. \"Sunny Shoreham\", ''Pilot'', February 2012, p71</ref>\n\n===Inter-war period===\nThe aerodrome became an airport for the adjacent towns of Brighton, [[Hove]] and Worthing. It was officially opened on 13 June 1936 under the name ''Brighton Hove and Worthing Joint Municipal Airport.'' The new terminal building was built in 1936 and was designed by Stavers Tiltman in the [[Art Deco]] style.<ref>{{PastScape|mnumber=1409758|mname=|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The terminal building is still in use and was designated a Grade II* [[listed building]] in 1984.\n\nIn 1937 one of the local flying schools received a contract to train pilots for the Royal Air Force and was known as No. 16 Elementary and Reserve Flying Training School initially using the [[de Havilland Tiger Moth]] which were later supplemented by the use of the [[Hawker Hart]] and [[Hawker Hind|Hind]]. With the start of the Second World War the training school moved away from Shoreham in August 1939.<ref name=\"brooks\">Brooks 1996, pp. 123\u2013130</ref>\n\n===Second World War===\nThe airfield started the [[World War II|Second World War]] in civilian hands until a detachment of [[Westland Lysander]]s of [[No. 225 Squadron RAF|225 Squadron]] arrived in July 1940 to undertake coastal patrols.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> With the nearby [[RAF Tangmere]] damaged by air raids the Fighter Interception Unit with the [[Bristol Beaufighter]] moved to Shoreham although they had problems with the grass runway.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> In October 1940 [[No. 422 Flight RAF|422 Flight]] arrived with the [[Hawker Hurricane]] operating as night-fighters. By October 1941 both units had moved away from Shoreham.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nThe airfield was regularly attacked during July and August 1941 and the next unit to arrive was No 11 Group Target Towing Flight in October 1941.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> Westland Lysanders were used to tow targets for fighter squadrons to practice air-firing.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> Lysanders and later the Supermarine Walrus were also based for search and rescue duties.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> In December 1941 a detachment of [[Hawker Hurricane]] fighters from 245 Squadron arrived at Shoreham to support the Tangmere-based squadrons. By August 1941 the fighters had moved on and only the 277 Squadron remained in the search and rescue, the Lysanders were replaced by the [[Boulton Paul Defiant]]s in May 1942.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nIn February 1943 the Defiants were replaced by [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s and in April 1943 the airfield became a practice camp to RAF Regiment gunners in the anti-aircract role.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> Lysanders appeared again but this time to tow targets for the regiment gunners.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> A gunnery training dome was built on the northern perimeter of the airfield that still survives into the 21st Century.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nIn April 1944 No. 345 (Free French) Squadron arrived with Spitfires to support the preparation for the [[Normandy invasion]]; the squadron was active on [[D-Day]] over the beaches and escorting glider formations.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> No 345 Squadron moved out in August 1944 and 277 Squadron in October 1944 and the airfield went into care and maintenance and was little used for the rest of war.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nThe airfield was bombed several times and a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]] was shot down by ground fire during one such attack, crash-landing near the terminal building.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pocock|first1=D A|title=The Royal Air Force Regiment; The Formative years to 1946|journal=Journal of the Royal Air Force Historical Society|date=1995|issue=15|page=23|oclc=21256749}}</ref>\n\nA [[B-17 Flying Fortress]] crash-landed at the airfield after being damaged during a raid on [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]. The consequent damage to the old guardhouse on the north side of the airfield can still be seen.\n\n===Post-Second World War===\nThe landing area was entirely grass until a [[Asphalt concrete|tarmac]] runway was built in 1981.\n\nIn 1949, F G Miles Engineering Ltd moved to Shoreham from Redhill Aerodrome and soon occupied the repaired Municipal Hangar.\n\n[[Beagle Aircraft]] Ltd (British Executive & General Aviation Ltd) was formed at Shoreham on 7 October 1960 and design drawings were begun a few weeks later for a new prototype twin-engine light transport aircraft. Built as the [[Beagle B.206]]X at Beagle's Rearsby factory near Leicester, this promising new type was completed at Shoreham and first flown by John Nicolson on 15 August 1961. Beagle Aircraft Ltd was nationalised in late 1966 and taken over by the British Motor Corporation but later entered receivership in late 1969 and soon closed down.\n\nIn 2006, due to mounting debts the airport was sold by the local authority to a property company on a 150-year lease. It was intended that the airport would provide increasing commercial flight activity for the conurbation on the coast nearby, particularly the city of Brighton & Hove.\n\nThe pre-war municipal hangar was [[listed building|listed Grade II]] in July 2007.\n\n===Present===\nThe airport is used by privately owned light aeroplanes, flying schools, and for light aircraft and helicopter maintenance and sales. A number of operators provide flying lessons, sight-seeing and pleasure flights, including the experience of flying in two [[T-6 Texan|T-6 Harvard]] World War II [[Trainer (aircraft)|training aircraft]].\n\nOn 2 May 2014, Brighton City Airport Ltd (BCAL) took ownership of the airport and its operations, which at the time was named Shoreham Airport, taking over from Albemarle.<ref name=\"worthingherald.co.uk\"/> Once the takeover was completed, the airport was officially renamed as Brighton City (Shoreham) Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flybrighton.com/about-us/|title=About Brighton City Airport \u2013 Flying With Us \u2013 Shoreham|website=flybrighton.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021170534/http://flybrighton.com/about-us/|archivedate=21 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Wild Life Festival===\nSince June 2015, Wild Life Festival, a live music event developed by [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] and [[Rudimental]] has been held at Brighton City Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/disclosure/82552#uHU3f1SQkodQ4jjp.99|title=Nas, Mark Ronson, Earl Sweatshirt added to Disclosure and Rudimental's Wild Life festival|work=NME.COM|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131094011/http://www.nme.com/news/disclosure/82552#uHU3f1SQkodQ4jjp.99|archivedate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==RAFA Shoreham Airshow==\n[[File:Fairey Swordfish 2 (6064836688).jpg|thumb|[[Fairey Swordfish]] torpedo bomber at 2011 airshow.]]\n\nThe airport used to host the [[Royal Air Forces Association]] (RAFA) [[Shoreham Airshow]] (for around 25 years). On 22 August 2015, a [[Hawker Hunter]] jet fighter taking part in the airshow [[2015 Shoreham Airshow crash|crashed]] onto the [[A27 road]] just outside Brighton City Airport, killing 11 people, and the show has not been held since.<ref name=\"BBC34034430\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-34034430 |title=Shoreham air crash death toll 'rises to 11' |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=23 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823150551/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-34034430 |archivedate=23 August 2015  }}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Shoreham Airport OSM.png|thumb|Brighton City Airport]]\nThere is one terminal building at the airport, together with flight indicator boards announcing all arrivals and departures, a live runway camera and a licensed restaurant called ''The Hummingbird Restaurant and Cafe''. The airport houses [[Northbrook College]]'s engineering department \u2013 a [[Centre of Vocational Excellence]] (CoVE) in Aerospace and Aviation. A number of aerospace and aviation and non-aviation commercial businesses have offices and workshops on the airport site and along the perimeter road. The largest operator is Flying Time Aviation, providing integrated commercial pilot training, with a fleet of Diamond Aircraft DA40s and DA42s.\n\nThe visitor centre features exhibits about the airport's history and area aviation history, a library and archive of related historic materials and guided tours of the airport.\n\n== Ground transport ==\nThe airport is served by [[Shoreham-by-Sea railway station|Shoreham-by-Sea]] station on the [[West Coastway Line]], {{convert|1|mi}} distant. A [[Train station#Halt|halt]], ''[[Bungalow Town Halt railway station|Bungalow Town Halt]]'', had been opened in 1910, just in front of the main building. In 1935 its name was changed to ''Shoreham Airport''. The station closed in 1940.\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\nVarious [[air taxi]] companies are based at the airport. [[Brighton City Airways]] operated out of the airport to [[Pontoise \u2013 Cormeilles Aerodrome|Paris Pontoise airport]] but ceased operations in 2013 after encountering problems setting up a point of entry at the French airport.\n<!-- NO NEWS ABOUT AIR ALDERNEY FOR 6 MONTHS AND WEBSITE HAS NOT CHANGED EITHER - NEED EVIDENCE THAT THERE IS CLEAR PROGRESS TOWARDS FLIGHTS TAKING PLACE... In March 2017,  [[Air Alderney]] had plans to operate flights to and from [[Alderney Airport|Alderney]] from September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/53873-air-alderney-eyes-uk-france-flights-using-islanders|title=Air Alderney eyes UK, France flights using Islanders|website=ch-aviation.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007094546/https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/53873-air-alderney-eyes-uk-france-flights-using-islanders|archivedate=7 October 2017}}</ref> As of January 2019 the airline was \"still working hard to obtain the relevant licensing\" to allow the service to operate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airalderney.gg/ |website=Air Alderney |accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> -->\n\n== South East Air Support Unit ==\nThe [[South East Air Support Unit]] formerly operated from Brighton City Airport. Previously [[Sussex Police Air Operations Unit]], the unit moved in summer 2007 to [[Dunsfold Aerodrome|Dunsfold Park]], west of [[Gatwick Airport]], before moving to its present base at [[Redhill Aerodrome]] in autumn 2013.\n\n== Shoreham Airport RFFS ==\nThe Shoreham Airport Rescue and Firefighting Service provides a professional fire-fighting capability at the airport during operating hours. Headed by a senior airport fire officer, the service's two watches (Blue Watch and Red Watch) man two fire appliances. The service has operated at the airport continuously for over 90 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarffs.co.uk/|title=Tennis Shoes and clothing online outlet UK sale : 2016 newest|website=www.sarffs.co.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424040513/http://www.sarffs.co.uk/|archivedate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrighton City Airport's aircraft fuelling service is operated as a department of the Rescue and Firefighting Service. There are three large mobile fuel bowsers for delivering both [[avgas]] and jet fuel to aircraft, including a service (accompanied by fire appliances) for fast delivery of fuel to police and coastguard emergency helicopters without disengaging their engines. Fuel technicians are attached to the firefighting watches and work the same shift pattern<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarffs.co.uk/fuel/fuel.html|title=Airport fuelling team webpage|website=sarffs.co.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813224424/http://www.sarffs.co.uk/fuel/fuel.html|archivedate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Film appearances ==\nDue to its listed period buildings and facilities, Brighton City Airport has been used by film-makers seeking to portray a small town airport, or even for historical reconstructions of scenes from the 1930s onwards. The airport has appeared in the [[Netflix]] TV series ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'' and three episodes of ''[[Agatha Christie's Poirot]]'' (\"[[Poirot Investigates#The Adventure of the Western Star|The Adventure of the Western Star]]\", \"[[Death in the Clouds]]\" and \"[[Lord Edgware Dies]]\").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0235681/|title=\"Agatha Christie's Poirot\" Lord Edgware Dies (TV Episode 2000) \u2013 IMDb|date=11 June 2000|work=IMDb|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209051154/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0235681/|archivedate=9 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvlocations.net/lordedgware.htm|title=Poirot Locations \u2013 Lord Edgware Dies|work=tvlocations.net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303050115/http://www.tvlocations.net/lordedgware.htm|archivedate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investigatingpoirot.blogspot.com.es/2013/08/episode-by-episode-lord-edgware-dies.html|title=Investigating Agatha Christie's Poirot: Episode-by-episode: Lord Edgware Dies|author=Eirik|work=investigatingpoirot.blogspot.com.es|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018174412/http://investigatingpoirot.blogspot.com.es/2013/08/episode-by-episode-lord-edgware-dies.html|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref> External shots of the airport were also used in the films ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/6808414.Secret_Da_Vinci_Code_airport_set_revealed/ | title=Secret Da Vinci Code airport set revealed | date=9 January 2006 | publisher=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]] | accessdate=16 September 2007 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819105007/http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/6808414.Secret_Da_Vinci_Code_airport_set_revealed/ | archivedate=19 August 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ''[[Woman in Gold (film)|Woman in Gold]]''. The airport was used in the feature-length documentary ''Angel Without Wings''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.factnotfictionfilms.com/aww.html | title=Angel Without Wings | date=31 March 2011 | work=Fact Not Fiction Films | accessdate=28 October 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110170519/http://www.factnotfictionfilms.com/aww.html | archivedate=10 November 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ''[[A Dark Reflection (2014 film)|A Dark Reflection]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*{{cite book|title=Sussex Airfields in the Second World War|first=Robin J.|last=Brooks|publisher=Countryside Books|location=Newbury, Berkshire, England|date=1996|isbn=1 85306 259 6}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category inline|Shoreham Airport}}\n* [http://www.flybrighton.com/  Brighton City Airport (official website)]\n\n{{Airports in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:1910 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Adur District]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1910]]\n[[Category:Airports in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in England]]\n\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Transport in West Sussex]]\n", "text_old": "{{confused|Brighton Airport}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox airport \n| name         = Brighton City Airport\n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image        = Brighton_City_Airport_Logo.png\n| image2       = Terminal Building at Shoreham Airport - geograph.org.uk - 573952.jpg\n| image-width  = 150\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA         = ESH\n| ICAO         = EGKA\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = \n| operator     = Brighton City Airport Ltd\n| city-served  = [[South East England|South East]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| location     = [[Lancing, West Sussex|Lancing]], [[West Sussex]]\n| elevation-f  = 7\n| elevation-m  = 2\n| coordinates  = {{coord|50|50|08|N|000|17|50|W|type:airport_region:GB-WSX|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = West Sussex\n| pushpin_label          = EGKA\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in West Sussex\n| website      = [http://www.flybrighton.com/ flybrighton.com]\n| metric-rwy   = Yes\n| r1-number    = 02/20\n| r1-length-f  = 3,399\n| r1-length-m  = 1,036\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number    = 06/24\n| r2-length-f  = 2,621\n| r2-length-m  = 799\n| r2-surface   = [[Grass]]\n| r3-number    = 13/31\n| r3-length-f  = 1,339\n| r3-length-m  = 408\n| r3-surface   = Grass\n| r4-number    = 02/20<BR><small>Unlicensed</small>\n| r4-length-f  = 2,297\n| r4-length-m  = 700\n| r4-surface   = [[Grass]]\n| stat-year    = 2018 \n| stat1-header = Passengers \n| stat1-data   = \u2013\n| stat2-header = Movements\n| stat2-data   = 39,224\n| footnotes    = Sources: UK [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] at [[National Air Traffic Services|NATS]]<ref name=\"aip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nats-uk.ead-it.com/public/index.php%3Foption=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=134&Itemid=183.html|title=NATS \u2013 AIS \u2013 Home|work=ead-it.com}}</ref> <br> Statistics from the [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|UK Civil Aviation Authority]]<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.caa.co.uk/Data-and-analysis/UK-aviation-market/Airports/Datasets/UK-Airport-data/Airport-data-2018/|title=Data and analysis \u2013 UK Civil Aviation Authority|website=www.caa.co.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100618/http://www.caa.co.uk/default.aspx?catid=80&pagetype=88&sglid=3&fld=2014Annual|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref>}}\n\n'''Brighton City Airport''' {{Airport codes|ESH|EGKA}}, also commonly known as '''Shoreham Airport''', is located in the [[Civil parish|parish]] of [[Lancing, West Sussex|Lancing]] in [[West Sussex]], England. It has a [[Civil Aviation Authority (United Kingdom)|CAA]] Public Use Aerodrome Licence that allows flights for the public transport of passengers or for flying instruction.\n\nFounded in 1910, it is the oldest airport in the UK and the oldest purpose-built commercial airport in the world.<ref name=\"Bloom 70\">Bloom, Nick. \"Sunny Shoreham\", ''Pilot'', February 2012, p70</ref> It is now owned by Brighton City Airport Ltd (BCAL).<ref name=\"worthingherald.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worthingherald.co.uk/news/local/new-plan-safeguards-future-of-shoreham-airport-1-6035934|title=New plan 'safeguards future of Shoreham Airport'|work=worthingherald.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502215824/http://www.worthingherald.co.uk/news/local/new-plan-safeguards-future-of-shoreham-airport-1-6035934|archivedate=2 May 2014}}</ref> The 1930s [[Art Deco]] terminal building designed by [[R Stavers Hessell Tiltman]] is [[listed building|listed]] grade II*.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=1353731&resourceID=5|title=Heritage Gateway \u2013 Results|website=www.heritagegateway.org.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813221550/http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=1353731&resourceID=5|archivedate=13 August 2017}}</ref> The airport is {{Convert|1|NM|abbr=on|lk=in}} west of [[Shoreham-by-Sea]]<ref name=\"aip\"/> at [[Lancing, West Sussex|Lancing]] in the [[Adur (district)|Adur]] district of West Sussex. It is situated immediately to the south of the [[A27 road]], between [[Brighton]] and [[Worthing]], and immediately to the north of the [[West Coastway Line|West Coastway]] railway line.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shoreham (Brighton City) Airport (6659107193).jpg|thumb|Interior of the terminal building]]\n[[File:shorehamrunway.jpg|thumb|View of Runway 02 from the [[West Coastway Line|West Coastway]] railway line]]\n\n===Foundation===\nThe first aviator to fly there was [[Harold H. Piffard]] in 1910; a memorial garden celebrates his flight.<ref name=\"Bloom 70\" /> The aerodrome was officially opened on 20 June 1911. The [[Cecil Pashley|first flying school]] opened in 1913.\n\n===First World War===\nDuring the [[World War I|First World War]] the aerodrome was used by the [[Royal Flying Corps]]. It was the departure point for some of the earlier flights, using [[Bl\u00e9riot XI|Bl\u00e9riot]]s<ref>Royal Flying Corps WW1 Bl\u00e9riot XI reconnaissance monoplane | {{cite web |url=http://aircraft-photographs.s3-website-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/aircraft-ww1-RFC-bleriot-XI-observation-monoplane.html |title=Archived Document |accessdate=21 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221052735/http://aircraft-photographs.s3-website-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/aircraft-ww1-RFC-bleriot-XI-observation-monoplane.html |archivedate=21 February 2015  }}</ref> and [[Royal Aircraft Factory B.E.2|BE]]s, to join the conflict across the [[English Channel|Channel]].<ref>Bloom, Nick. \"Sunny Shoreham\", ''Pilot'', February 2012, p71</ref>\n\n===Inter-war period===\nThe aerodrome became an airport for the adjacent towns of Brighton, [[Hove]] and Worthing. It was officially opened on 13 June 1936 under the name ''Brighton Hove and Worthing Joint Municipal Airport.'' The new terminal building was built in 1936 and was designed by Stavers Tiltman in the [[Art Deco]] style.<ref>{{PastScape|mnumber=1409758|mname=|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The terminal building is still in use and was designated a Grade II* [[listed building]] in 1984.\n\nIn 1937 one of the local flying schools received a contract to train pilots for the Royal Air Force and was known as No. 16 Elementary and Reserve Flying Training School initially using the [[de Havilland Tiger Moth]] which were later supplemented by the use of the [[Hawker Hart]] and [[Hawker Hind|Hind]]. With the start of the Second World War the training school moved away from Shoreham in August 1939.<ref name=\"brooks\">Brooks 1996, pp. 123\u2013130</ref>\n\n===Second World War===\nThe airfield started the [[World War II|Second World War]] in civilian hands until a detachment of [[Westland Lysander]]s of [[No. 225 Squadron RAF|225 Squadron]] arrived in July 1940 to undertake coastal patrols.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> With the nearby [[RAF Tangmere]] damaged by air raids the Fighter Interception Unit with the [[Bristol Beaufighter]] moved to Shoreham although they had problems with the grass runway.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> In October 1940 [[No. 422 Flight RAF|422 Flight]] arrived with the [[Hawker Hurricane]] operating as night-fighters. By October 1941 both units had moved away from Shoreham.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nThe airfield was regularly attacked during July and August 1941 and the next unit to arrive was No 11 Group Target Towing Flight in October 1941.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> Westland Lysanders were used to tow targets for fighter squadrons to practice air-firing.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> Lysanders and later the Supermarine Walrus were also based for search and rescue duties.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> In December 1941 a detachment of [[Hawker Hurricane]] fighters from 245 Squadron arrived at Shoreham to support the Tangmere-based squadrons. By August 1941 the fighters had moved on and only the 277 Squadron remained in the search and rescue, the Lysanders were replaced by the [[Boulton Paul Defiant]]s in May 1942.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nIn February 1943 the Defiants were replaced by [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s and in April 1943 the airfield became a practice camp to RAF Regiment gunners in the anti-aircract role.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> Lysanders appeared again but this time to tow targets for the regiment gunners.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> A gunnery training dome was built on the northern perimeter of the airfield that still survives into the 21st Century.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nIn April 1944 No. 345 (Free French) Squadron arrived with Spitfires to support the preparation for the [[Normandy invasion]]; the squadron was active on [[D-Day]] over the beaches and escorting glider formations.<ref name=\"brooks\" /> No 345 Squadron moved out in August 1944 and 277 Squadron in October 1944 and the airfield went into care and maintenance and was little used for the rest of war.<ref name=\"brooks\" />\n\nThe airfield was bombed several times and a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]] was shot down by ground fire during one such attack, crash-landing near the terminal building.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pocock|first1=D A|title=The Royal Air Force Regiment; The Formative years to 1946|journal=Journal of the Royal Air Force Historical Society|date=1995|issue=15|page=23|oclc=21256749}}</ref>\n\nA [[B-17 Flying Fortress]] crash-landed at the airfield after being damaged during a raid on [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]. The consequent damage to the old guardhouse on the north side of the airfield can still be seen.\n\n===Post-Second World War===\nThe landing area was entirely grass until a [[Asphalt concrete|tarmac]] runway was built in 1981.\n\nIn 1949, F G Miles Engineering Ltd moved to Shoreham from Redhill Aerodrome and soon occupied the repaired Municipal Hangar.\n\n[[Beagle Aircraft]] Ltd (British Executive & General Aviation Ltd) was formed at Shoreham on 7 October 1960 and design drawings were begun a few weeks later for a new prototype twin-engine light transport aircraft. Built as the [[Beagle B.206]]X at Beagle's Rearsby factory near Leicester, this promising new type was completed at Shoreham and first flown by John Nicolson on 15 August 1961. Beagle Aircraft Ltd was nationalised in late 1966 and taken over by the British Motor Corporation but later entered receivership in late 1969 and soon closed down.\n\nIn 2006, due to mounting debts the airport was sold by the local authority to a property company on a 150-year lease. It was intended that the airport would provide increasing commercial flight activity for the conurbation on the coast nearby, particularly the city of Brighton & Hove.\n\nThe pre-war municipal hangar was [[listed building|listed Grade II]] in July 2007.\n\n===Present===\nThe airport is used by privately owned light aeroplanes, flying schools, and for light aircraft and helicopter maintenance and sales. A number of operators provide flying lessons, sight-seeing and pleasure flights, including the experience of flying in two [[T-6 Texan|T-6 Harvard]] World War II [[Trainer (aircraft)|training aircraft]].\n\nOn 2 May 2014, Brighton City Airport Ltd (BCAL) took ownership of the airport and its operations, which at the time was named Shoreham Airport, taking over from Albemarle.<ref name=\"worthingherald.co.uk\"/> Once the takeover was completed, the airport was officially renamed as Brighton City (Shoreham) Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flybrighton.com/about-us/|title=About Brighton City Airport \u2013 Flying With Us \u2013 Shoreham|website=flybrighton.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021170534/http://flybrighton.com/about-us/|archivedate=21 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Wild Life Festival===\nSince June 2015, Wild Life Festival, a live music event developed by [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] and [[Rudimental]] has been held at Brighton City Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/disclosure/82552#uHU3f1SQkodQ4jjp.99|title=Nas, Mark Ronson, Earl Sweatshirt added to Disclosure and Rudimental's Wild Life festival|work=NME.COM|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131094011/http://www.nme.com/news/disclosure/82552#uHU3f1SQkodQ4jjp.99|archivedate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==RAFA Shoreham Airshow==\n[[File:Fairey Swordfish 2 (6064836688).jpg|thumb|[[Fairey Swordfish]] torpedo bomber at 2011 airshow.]]\n\nThe airport used to host the [[Royal Air Forces Association]] (RAFA) [[Shoreham Airshow]] (for around 25 years). On 22 August 2015, a [[Hawker Hunter]] jet fighter taking part in the airshow [[2015 Shoreham Airshow crash|crashed]] onto the [[A27 road]] just outside Brighton City Airport, killing 11 people, and the show has not been held since.<ref name=\"BBC34034430\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-34034430 |title=Shoreham air crash death toll 'rises to 11' |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=23 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823150551/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-34034430 |archivedate=23 August 2015  }}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Shoreham Airport OSM.png|thumb|Brighton City Airport]]\nThere is one terminal building at the airport, together with flight indicator boards announcing all arrivals and departures, a live runway camera and a licensed restaurant called ''The Hummingbird Restaurant and Cafe''. The airport houses [[Northbrook College]]'s engineering department \u2013 a [[Centre of Vocational Excellence]] (CoVE) in Aerospace and Aviation. A number of aerospace and aviation and non-aviation commercial businesses have offices and workshops on the airport site and along the perimeter road. The largest operator is Flying Time Aviation, providing integrated commercial pilot training, with a fleet of Diamond Aircraft DA40s and DA42s.\n\nThe visitor centre features exhibits about the airport's history and area aviation history, a library and archive of related historic materials and guided tours of the airport.\n\n== Ground transport ==\nThe airport is served by [[Shoreham-by-Sea railway station|Shoreham-by-Sea]] station on the [[West Coastway Line]], {{convert|1|mi}} distant. A [[Train station#Halt|halt]], ''[[Bungalow Town Halt railway station|Bungalow Town Halt]]'', had been opened in 1910, just in front of the main building. In 1935 its name was changed to ''Shoreham Airport''. The station closed in 1940.\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\nVarious [[air taxi]] companies are based at the airport. [[Brighton City Airways]] operated out of the airport to [[Pontoise \u2013 Cormeilles Aerodrome|Paris Pontoise airport]] but ceased operations in 2013 after encountering problems setting up a point of entry at the French airport.\n<!-- NO NEWS ABOUT AIR ALDERNEY FOR 6 MONTHS AND WEBSITE HAS NOT CHANGED EITHER - NEED EVIDENCE THAT THERE IS CLEAR PROGRESS TOWARDS FLIGHTS TAKING PLACE... In March 2017,  [[Air Alderney]] had plans to operate flights to and from [[Alderney Airport|Alderney]] from September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/53873-air-alderney-eyes-uk-france-flights-using-islanders|title=Air Alderney eyes UK, France flights using Islanders|website=ch-aviation.com|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007094546/https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/53873-air-alderney-eyes-uk-france-flights-using-islanders|archivedate=7 October 2017}}</ref> As of January 2019 the airline was \"still working hard to obtain the relevant licensing\" to allow the service to operate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airalderney.gg/ |website=Air Alderney |accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> -->\n\n== South East Air Support Unit ==\nThe [[South East Air Support Unit]] formerly operated from Brighton City Airport. Previously [[Sussex Police Air Operations Unit]], the unit moved in summer 2007 to [[Dunsfold Aerodrome|Dunsfold Park]], west of [[Gatwick Airport]], before moving to its present base at [[Redhill Aerodrome]] in autumn 2013.\n\n== Shoreham Airport RFFS ==\nThe Shoreham Airport Rescue and Firefighting Service provides a professional fire-fighting capability at the airport during operating hours. Headed by a senior airport fire officer, the service's two watches (Blue Watch and Red Watch) man two fire appliances. The service has operated at the airport continuously for over 90 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarffs.co.uk/|title=Tennis Shoes and clothing online outlet UK sale : 2016 newest|website=www.sarffs.co.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424040513/http://www.sarffs.co.uk/|archivedate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrighton City Airport's aircraft fuelling service is operated as a department of the Rescue and Firefighting Service. There are three large mobile fuel bowsers for delivering both [[avgas]] and jet fuel to aircraft, including a service (accompanied by fire appliances) for fast delivery of fuel to police and coastguard emergency helicopters without disengaging their engines. Fuel technicians are attached to the firefighting watches and work the same shift pattern<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarffs.co.uk/fuel/fuel.html|title=Airport fuelling team webpage|website=sarffs.co.uk|accessdate=24 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813224424/http://www.sarffs.co.uk/fuel/fuel.html|archivedate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Film appearances ==\nDue to its listed period buildings and facilities, Brighton City Airport has been used by film-makers seeking to portray a small town airport, or even for historical reconstructions of scenes from the 1930s onwards. The airport has appeared in the [[Netflix]] TV series ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'' and three episodes of ''[[Agatha Christie's Poirot]]'' (\"[[Poirot Investigates#The Adventure of the Western Star|The Adventure of the Western Star]]\", \"[[Death in the Clouds]]\" and \"[[Lord Edgware Dies]]\").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0235681/|title=\"Agatha Christie's Poirot\" Lord Edgware Dies (TV Episode 2000) \u2013 IMDb|date=11 June 2000|work=IMDb|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209051154/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0235681/|archivedate=9 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvlocations.net/lordedgware.htm|title=Poirot Locations \u2013 Lord Edgware Dies|work=tvlocations.net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303050115/http://www.tvlocations.net/lordedgware.htm|archivedate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investigatingpoirot.blogspot.com.es/2013/08/episode-by-episode-lord-edgware-dies.html|title=Investigating Agatha Christie's Poirot: Episode-by-episode: Lord Edgware Dies|author=Eirik|work=investigatingpoirot.blogspot.com.es|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018174412/http://investigatingpoirot.blogspot.com.es/2013/08/episode-by-episode-lord-edgware-dies.html|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref> External shots of the airport were also used in the films ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/6808414.Secret_Da_Vinci_Code_airport_set_revealed/ | title=Secret Da Vinci Code airport set revealed | date=9 January 2006 | publisher=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]] | accessdate=16 September 2007 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819105007/http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/6808414.Secret_Da_Vinci_Code_airport_set_revealed/ | archivedate=19 August 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ''[[Woman in Gold (film)|Woman in Gold]]''. The airport was used in the feature-length documentary ''Angel Without Wings''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.factnotfictionfilms.com/aww.html | title=Angel Without Wings | date=31 March 2011 | work=Fact Not Fiction Films | accessdate=28 October 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110170519/http://www.factnotfictionfilms.com/aww.html | archivedate=10 November 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and ''[[A Dark Reflection (2014 film)|A Dark Reflection]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*{{cite book|title=Sussex Airfields in the Second World War|first=Robin J.|last=Brooks|publisher=Countryside Books|location=Newbury, Berkshire, England|date=1996|isbn=1 85306 259 6}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category inline|Shoreham Airport}}\n* [http://www.flybrighton.com/  Brighton City Airport (official website)]\n\n{{Airports in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:1910 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Adur District]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1910]]\n[[Category:Airports in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Transport in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in England]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Reordered cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brighton_City_Airport"}
{"title_page": "John F. Aiso", "text_new": "{{short description|American military officer}}\n{{short description|American Judge}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = John F Aiso\n| image = John_Aiso_in_uniform,_c._1941-1945.png\n|office      = [[California Courts of Appeal]]\n|appointer   = [[Ronald Reagan]] \n|term_start  = November 4, 1968\n|term_end    = December 31, 1972\n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|office1      = [[Los Angeles County Superior Court]]\n|appointer1   = [[Goodwin Knight]] \n|term_start1  = September 11, 1957 \n|term_end1    = November 1968\n|predecessor1 = \n|successor1   = \n| birth_name = John Fujio Aiso\n| birth_date = December 14, 1909\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1987|12|29|1909|12|14}}\n| death_place = Los Angeles, California\n| party = \n| education = [[Brown University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Harvard Law School]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])}}<br>[[Chuo University]] {{small|([[Law of Japan|Japanese Law]])}} \n| website = \n| signature = \n| allegiance = {{Flagu|United States|1960}}\n| branch = [[United States Army]]\n| serviceyears = 1941-1947\n| rank = {{Dodseal|USAO5-2015|25}} [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lt Col]]\n| unit = Director, [[Military Intelligence Service (United States)|Military Intelligence Service Language School]]\n| battles = [[World War II]]\n| awards = [[Legion of Merit]]<br />[[Order of the Rising Sun#3rd Class, Gold Rays with Neck Ribbon|Order of the Rising Sun]] \n}}\n'''John Fujio Aiso''' ({{lang-ja|\u76f8\u78ef \u85e4\u96c4}}, December 14, 1909 \u2013 December 29, 1987) was an [[United States|American]] [[nisei]] [[military]] leader, [[lawyer]] and [[judge]]. Aiso was the Director and head instructor of the [[Military Intelligence Service Language School]], and the highest-ranking Japanese American in the U.S. Army during [[World War II]]. He was also the first Japanese American appointed as a judge in the [[contiguous United States]].<ref name=Aiso_MIS>{{Cite book|title=John Aiso and the M.I.S.|last=Ichinokuchi|first=Tad|publisher=MIS Club of Southern California|year=1988}}</ref><ref name='CA Courts bio'>California Courts, \"[http://www.courts.ca.gov/documents/AisoJ.pdf John F. Aiso biography]\"</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], Aiso was an excellent student, despite encounters with anti-Japanese prejudice. He later described one of his first memories as being called a \"Jap\" by an elderly woman on a streetcar, explaining the amount of effort he put into his schoolwork was largely to counteract such comments. He was elected student body president of his junior high school in 1922, but the victory proved to be short lived: parents protested a Japanese American holding the position, and student government was suspended until Aiso left the school. He went on to attend [[Hollywood High School]], where he drew national attention when he won the school's oratorical competition on the U.S. Constitution in 1926. However, he was once again forced to step down, when he was told he could not compete at the national championship and would instead have to coach his runner up.<ref name=Nakamura>{{cite web|last=Nakamura |first=Kelli Y. |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/John%20Aiso/ |title=John Aiso |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nAfter graduating at the top of his Hollywood High School class in 1926, Aiso spent a year in Japan, studying Japanese at [[Seijo University]] in [[Tokyo]]. He returned to the United States after receiving a scholarship to attend [[Brown University]], where he captained the debate team and majored in economics, graduating ''[[cum laude]]'' and serving as class valedictorian in 1931. He continued his studies at [[Harvard Law School]], completing his degree in 1934.<ref name=Aiso_MIS/><ref name=JAVA>Japanese American Veterans Association. \"[http://www.javadc.org/Hall%20of%20Famers.htm Hall of Famers]: Col. John F. Aiso, Military Intelligence Corps Hall of Fame (1991).\" Retrieved 10 November 2014.</ref>\n\nBetween 1935 and 1952, he worked in private practice in [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City|New York]]. In 1936, he spent another year in Tokyo, working with Japanese banks on behalf of his U.S. law firm, and while there he studied Japanese law at [[Chuo University]]. From 1937 to 1940, he worked for the [[British American Tobacco]] Company in Japanese-occupied [[Manchukuo|Manchuria]].<ref name=Nakamura/><ref name=JAVA/>\n\nAfter his return to the United States, Aiso was drafted into the army, reporting for active duty in April 1941. Originally stationed at [[Fort MacArthur]], Aiso was assigned to menial tasks due to discrimination, and was working in the motor pool when his proficiency in the Japanese language was recognized by [[Fourth United States Army|Fourth Army]] [[G-2 (intelligence)|G-2]] officer, Capt. Kai E. Rasmussen, who was tasked with developing a Japanese language school, and transferred Aiso to the hastily formed (and, at first, secret) [[Military Intelligence Service (United States)|Military Intelligence Service]] Language School (MISLS).<ref name=JAVA/> Recruited by MISLS head Lt Col John Weckerling as an instructor at the school, Aiso, then a [[Private first class#United States|Private First Class]], couldn't be expected to teach [[Officer (armed forces)|officers]], and Japanese Americans were prohibited from being commissioned at the time, so he was to be discharged, transferred to Reserve service, and hired as a War Department Civilian.<ref name=Aiso_MIS/>\n\nAiso distinguished himself in his role, earning praise from his commanders and his fellow instructors, and was soon appointed the Director of Academic Training, a position normally held by a Lieutenant Colonel. When the Chief of Army Intelligence, Gen [[Clayton Lawrence Bissell]], visited the school in 1944, he was outraged that a civilian was placed in command of military personnel, and went back to Washington to demand a direct commission for Aiso to [[Major (United States)|Major]]. In this position, he became the highest-ranking [[Japanese American]] in the [[United States Army]] during the Second World War, eventually separating from active duty with the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]].<ref name=Aiso_MIS/>\n\nUnder his inspiring leadership as director of academic training, the MISLS rapidly expanded. He recruited and trained a staff of over 150, developed course materials, and set the highest academic standards.<ref name=Nakamura/> The more than 6,000 graduates contributed immeasurably to the American victory over Imperial Japan and to winning the peace that followed.<ref>Ano, Masaharu. \"[http://www.mnhs.org/market/mhspress/minnesotahistory/featuredarticles/4507273-287/ Loyal Linguists: Nisei of World War II Learned Japanese in Minnesota] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310034601/http://www.mnhs.org/market/mhspress/minnesotahistory/featuredarticles/4507273-287/ |date=2014-03-10 }},\" ''Minnesota History Quarterly'', Fall 1977 (45:7), pp 273-87.</ref> (General [[Charles A. Willoughby|Charles Willoughby]] credited Aiso's MIS graduates with shortening the war by two years and saving close to a million lives.)<ref name=Nakamura/>\n\nAfter the Allied victory in August 1945, Aiso refocused the MISLS curriculum to prepare students for roles in the [[occupation of Japan]]. In January 1946, he would transfer to Gen [[Douglas MacArthur]]'s staff as a legal assistant under MacArthur's [[G-2 (intelligence)|G-2]] chief, Gen [[Charles A. Willoughby]], working in the investigation and enforcement of the political purge dictated by the [[Potsdam Declaration]]. Aiso was released from active duty and returned to Los Angeles in February 1947, returning to private law practice .<ref name=Aiso_MIS/> He would later be promoted to a [[colonel]] in the [[United States Army Reserve|Army Reserve]], before retiring in 1965.<ref name=JAVA/>\n\nIn 1950, he received an honorary master's degree from Brown University.<ref name=Brunoniana>\"[http://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/Databases/Encyclopedia/search.php?serial=H0200 Honorary Degrees],\" from Martha Mitchell's ''Encyclopedia Brunoniana''</ref> In 1952, he served as a Commissioner for one year. Aiso was then appointed to the Los Angeles Municipal Court in 1953, where he served until he was elevated to the [[Los Angeles Superior Court]] in 1957. He was the first [[Japanese American]] to enter the California State Judiciary when then Governor [[Ronald Reagan]] appointed Aiso as an Associate Justice of the [[California Court of Appeal]], Second Appellate District, on November 4, 1968.<ref name='CA Courts bio'/>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\nPresident [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] awarded him the [[Legion of Merit]] in 1965 for his service during World War II. In 1984, the [[Emperor of Japan]] awarded him the 3rd Class [[Order of the Rising Sun]] for his contributions to understanding and friendship between the United States and Japan. He was inducted into the [[Military Intelligence Hall of Fame|Military Intelligence Corps Hall of Fame]] in 1991.<ref name=Nakamura/><ref name=JAVA/> The Aiso Library at the [[Defense Language Institute]] (DLI) Foreign Language Center is named in his honor for his contributions as the chief instructor of MISLS, the predecessor of DLI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dlilibrary.monterey.army.mil/aisolib.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-06-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060617034943/http://dlilibrary.monterey.army.mil/aisolib.htm |archivedate=2006-06-17 }}</ref> In the [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]] community of [[Los Angeles]], a one-block segment of [[San Pedro Street]] between Temple Boulevard and 1st Street has been renamed Judge John Aiso Street in his honor.\n\n==Death==\nJohn Aiso died December 29, 1987, from a head injury sustained in an attempted mugging. Aiso, 78, was filling his car at a Hollywood gas station when he was attacked and knocked to the pavement; he died two weeks later in a Burbank hospital.<ref>Morrison, Pat; O'Donnell, Santiago. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-31/local/me-7802_1_john-aiso John Aiso, Prominent Nisei and Jurist, Dies After Mugger's Attack],\" (31 December 1987) ''Los Angeles Times''. Retrieved 10 November 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aiso, John F.}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American jurists of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Hollywood High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Municipal judges in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Superior court judges in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American military officer}}\n{{short description|American Judge}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = John F Aiso\n| image = John_Aiso_in_uniform,_c._1941-1945.png\n|office      = [[California Courts of Appeal]]\n|appointer   = [[Ronald Reagan]] \n|term_start  = November 4, 1968\n|term_end    = December 31, 1972\n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|office1      = [[Los Angeles County Superior Court]]\n|appointer1   = [[Goodwin Knight]] \n|term_start1  = September 11, 1957 \n|term_end1    = November 1968\n|predecessor1 = \n|successor1   = \n| birth_name = John Fujio Aiso\n| birth_date = December 14, 1909\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1987|12|29|1909|12|14}}\n| death_place = Los Angeles, California\n| party = \n| education = [[Brown University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Harvard Law School]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])}}<br>[[Chuo University]] {{small|([[Law of Japan|Japanese Law]])}} \n| website = \n| signature = \n| allegiance = {{Flagu|United States|1960}}\n| branch = [[United States Army]]\n| serviceyears = 1941-1947\n| rank = {{Dodseal|USAO5-2015|25}} [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lt Col]]\n| unit = Director, [[Military Intelligence Service (United States)|Military Intelligence Service Language School]]\n| battles = [[World War II]]\n| awards = [[Legion of Merit]]<br />[[Order_of_the_Rising_Sun#3rd_Class,_Gold_Rays_with_Neck_Ribbon|Order of the Rising Sun]] \n}}\n'''John Fujio Aiso''' ({{lang-ja|\u76f8\u78ef \u85e4\u96c4}}, December 14, 1909 \u2013 December 29, 1987) was an [[United States|American]] [[nisei]] [[military]] leader, [[lawyer]] and [[judge]]. Aiso was the Director and head instructor of the [[Military Intelligence Service Language School]], and the highest-ranking Japanese American in the U.S. Army during [[World War II]]. He was also the first Japanese American appointed as a judge in the [[contiguous United States]].<ref name=Aiso_MIS>{{Cite book|title=John Aiso and the M.I.S.|last=Ichinokuchi|first=Tad|publisher=MIS Club of Southern California|year=1988}}</ref><ref name='CA Courts bio'>California Courts, \"[http://www.courts.ca.gov/documents/AisoJ.pdf John F. Aiso biography]\"</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], Aiso was an excellent student, despite encounters with anti-Japanese prejudice. He later described one of his first memories as being called a \"Jap\" by an elderly woman on a streetcar, explaining the amount of effort he put into his schoolwork was largely to counteract such comments. He was elected student body president of his junior high school in 1922, but the victory proved to be short lived: parents protested a Japanese American holding the position, and student government was suspended until Aiso left the school. He went on to attend [[Hollywood High School]], where he drew national attention when he won the school's oratorical competition on the U.S. Constitution in 1926. However, he was once again forced to step down, when he was told he could not compete at the national championship and would instead have to coach his runner up.<ref name=Nakamura>{{cite web|last=Nakamura |first=Kelli Y. |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/John%20Aiso/ |title=John Aiso |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nAfter graduating at the top of his Hollywood High School class in 1926, Aiso spent a year in Japan, studying Japanese at [[Seijo University]] in [[Tokyo]]. He returned to the United States after receiving a scholarship to attend [[Brown University]], where he captained the debate team and majored in economics, graduating ''[[cum laude]]'' and serving as class valedictorian in 1931. He continued his studies at [[Harvard Law School]], completing his degree in 1934.<ref name=Aiso_MIS/><ref name=JAVA>Japanese American Veterans Association. \"[http://www.javadc.org/Hall%20of%20Famers.htm Hall of Famers]: Col. John F. Aiso, Military Intelligence Corps Hall of Fame (1991).\" Retrieved 10 November 2014.</ref>\n\nBetween 1935 and 1952, he worked in private practice in [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City|New York]]. In 1936, he spent another year in Tokyo, working with Japanese banks on behalf of his U.S. law firm, and while there he studied Japanese law at [[Chuo University]]. From 1937 to 1940, he worked for the [[British American Tobacco]] Company in Japanese-occupied [[Manchukuo|Manchuria]].<ref name=Nakamura/><ref name=JAVA/>\n\nAfter his return to the United States, Aiso was drafted into the army, reporting for active duty in April 1941. Originally stationed at [[Fort MacArthur]], Aiso was assigned to menial tasks due to discrimination, and was working in the motor pool when his proficiency in the Japanese language was recognized by [[Fourth United States Army|Fourth Army]] [[G-2 (intelligence)|G-2]] officer, Capt. Kai E. Rasmussen, who was tasked with developing a Japanese language school, and transferred Aiso to the hastily formed (and, at first, secret) [[Military Intelligence Service (United States)|Military Intelligence Service]] Language School (MISLS).<ref name=JAVA/> Recruited by MISLS head Lt Col John Weckerling as an instructor at the school, Aiso, then a [[Private_first_class#United_States|Private First Class]], couldn't be expected to teach [[Officer (armed forces)|officers]], and Japanese Americans were prohibited from being commissioned at the time, so he was to be discharged, transfered to Reserve service, and hired as a War Department Civilian.<ref name=Aiso_MIS/> \n\nAiso distinguished himself in his role, earning praise from his commanders and his fellow instructors, and was soon appointed the Director of Academic Training, a position normally held by a Lieutenant Colonel. When the Chief of Army Intelligence, Gen [[Clayton Lawrence Bissell]], visited the school in 1944, he was outraged that a civilian was placed in command of military personnel, and went back to Washington to demand a direct commission for Aiso to [[Major (United States)|Major]]. In this position, he became the highest-ranking [[Japanese American]] in the [[United States Army]] during the Second World War, eventually separating from active duty with the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]].<ref name=Aiso_MIS/>\n\nUnder his inspiring leadership as director of academic training, the MISLS rapidly expanded. He recruited and trained a staff of over 150, developed course materials, and set the highest academic standards.<ref name=Nakamura/> The more than 6,000 graduates contributed immeasurably to the American victory over Imperial Japan and to winning the peace that followed.<ref>Ano, Masaharu. \"[http://www.mnhs.org/market/mhspress/minnesotahistory/featuredarticles/4507273-287/ Loyal Linguists: Nisei of World War II Learned Japanese in Minnesota] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310034601/http://www.mnhs.org/market/mhspress/minnesotahistory/featuredarticles/4507273-287/ |date=2014-03-10 }},\" ''Minnesota History Quarterly'', Fall 1977 (45:7), pp 273-87.</ref> (General [[Charles A. Willoughby|Charles Willoughby]] credited Aiso's MIS graduates with shortening the war by two years and saving close to a million lives.)<ref name=Nakamura/>\n\nAfter the Allied victory in August 1945, Aiso refocused the MISLS curriculum to prepare students for roles in the [[occupation of Japan]]. In January 1946, he would transfer to Gen [[Douglas MacArthur]]'s staff as a legal assistant under MacArthur's [[G-2 (intelligence)|G-2]] chief, Gen [[Charles A. Willoughby]], working in the investigation and enforcement of the political purge dictated by the [[Potsdam Declaration]]. Aiso was released from active duty and returned to Los Angeles in February 1947, returning to private law practice .<ref name=Aiso_MIS/> He would later be promoted to a [[colonel]] in the [[United States Army Reserve|Army Reserve]], before retiring in 1965.<ref name=JAVA/>\n\nIn 1950, he received an honorary master's degree from Brown University.<ref name=Brunoniana>\"[http://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/Databases/Encyclopedia/search.php?serial=H0200 Honorary Degrees],\" from Martha Mitchell's ''Encyclopedia Brunoniana''</ref> In 1952, he served as a Commissioner for one year. Aiso was then appointed to the Los Angeles Municipal Court in 1953, where he served until he was elevated to the [[Los Angeles Superior Court]] in 1957. He was the first [[Japanese American]] to enter the California State Judiciary when then Governor [[Ronald Reagan]] appointed Aiso as an Associate Justice of the [[California Court of Appeal]], Second Appellate District, on November 4, 1968.<ref name='CA Courts bio'/>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\nPresident [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] awarded him the [[Legion of Merit]] in 1965 for his service during World War II. In 1984, the [[Emperor of Japan]] awarded him the 3rd Class [[Order of the Rising Sun]] for his contributions to understanding and friendship between the United States and Japan. He was inducted into the [[Military Intelligence Hall of Fame|Military Intelligence Corps Hall of Fame]] in 1991.<ref name=Nakamura/><ref name=JAVA/> The Aiso Library at the [[Defense Language Institute]] (DLI) Foreign Language Center is named in his honor for his contributions as the chief instructor of MISLS, the predecessor of DLI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dlilibrary.monterey.army.mil/aisolib.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-06-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060617034943/http://dlilibrary.monterey.army.mil/aisolib.htm |archivedate=2006-06-17 }}</ref> In the [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]] community of [[Los Angeles]], a one-block segment of [[San Pedro Street]] between Temple Boulevard and 1st Street has been renamed Judge John Aiso Street in his honor.\n\n==Death==\nJohn Aiso died December 29, 1987, from a head injury sustained in an attempted mugging. Aiso, 78, was filling his car at a Hollywood gas station when he was attacked and knocked to the pavement; he died two weeks later in a Burbank hospital.<ref>Morrison, Pat; O'Donnell, Santiago. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-31/local/me-7802_1_john-aiso John Aiso, Prominent Nisei and Jurist, Dies After Mugger's Attack],\" (31 December 1987) ''Los Angeles Times''. Retrieved 10 November 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aiso, John F.}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American jurists of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Hollywood High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Municipal judges in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Burbank, California]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Superior court judges in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: transfered \u2192 transferred", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_F._Aiso"}
{"title_page": "Vicinal tramway", "text_new": "The '''Tramways vicinaux''' or '''Buurtspoorwegen''' were a system of [[narrow-gauge]] [[light rail|tramway]]s or local [[railway]]s in [[Belgium]], which covered the whole country and had a greater route length than the mainline railway system. They were {{RailGauge|1000mm}} gauge ([[metre gauge]]) and included electrified city lines and rural lines using [[steam locomotive]]s and [[Diesel engine|diesel]] railcars; half the system was electrified.\n\nThe company gradually switched to buses and dismantled the tram tracks. Only the [[Belgian coast tram|coastal line]], the [[Charleroi]] metro and the short line to the caves at [[Han-sur-Lesse]] are still in commercial use; four museums hold significant collections of rolling stock, including the museum at [[Schepdaal]] and the [[ASVi museum]] in [[Thuin]].\n\nThe longest ({{convert|11|km|abbr=on}}) and oldest (40 years) [[tourist tramway]] is the ''[[Tramway Touristique de l'Aisne]]'', or 'TTA', between [[Erez\u00e9e]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Dochamps|fr}}. A sponsoring group called 'Tramania' has supported various tramway preservation initiatives for 13 years, in particular financing construction of the Thuin museum and car restoration for TTA.\n\n==NMVB / SNCV==\nLegislation allowing the construction of rural tramways was passed in 1875, followed by a new law in 1885. The result was the creation of the national Vicinal tramway company \u2013 ''Nationale Maatschappij van Buurtspoorwegen (NMVB)'' in [[Dutch language|Dutch]], ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 nationale des chemins de fer vicinaux (SNCV)'' in [[French language|French]]. The majority of lines were {{Track gauge|1000mm|allk=on}}, although until 1921 many in the Antwerp area were {{Track gauge|1067mm|lk=on}} gauge, later [[Track gauge conversion|re-gauged]]. Many lines were built alongside roads, and carried considerable quantities of freight (especially timber and agricultural produce) as well as passengers.\n\n[[World War I]] and [[World War II]] saw greatly increased traffic despite some wartime damage. The non-electric network reached a peak of approximately {{convert|3,938|km}} in 1925, but soon parts started to close as usage of [[bus]]es, [[lorry|lorries]] and electric trams increased. Starting from 1924, the NMVB / SNCV started to operate buses (either owned or hired).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zone01.be/artikel/de-eerste-nmvb-busdiensten|title=De eerste NMVB busdiensten {{!}} Tijdlijn {{!}} Zone 01|website=www.zone01.be|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref> At this time, the electric tramway network was already {{convert|523|km}} in length. In 1939, the NMVB / SNCV operated 161 regular bus lines amounting to {{convert|279|km||abbr=}}.\n\nAfter World War II lorries, buses and cars deprived the trams of much of their business. The electric network reached a peak of {{convert|1,528|km}} in 1950. The whole network (electric and non-electric) was still approximately {{convert|4,236|km}} in length (the peak of {{convert|4,811|km}} was in 1945), but by 1960 had been reduced to only {{convert|977|km}}. On several rural lines, passenger tramways were replaced by buses but NMVB / SNCV kept running freight trams until it wasn't profitable anymore.\n\nIn 1977, the buses of the Belgian railways ([[SNCB/NMBS]]) were transferred to SNCV/NMVB. The tramways from [[Brussels]] to [[Wemmel]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Koningslo|nl}} and [[Grimbergen]] closed in 1978.\n\n[[File:Belgium.geohive.gif|thumb|Map of Belgium, its districts and major cities]]\nPolitical federalism within Belgium from 1980 onwards saw the splitting of many national institutions into separate bodies for [[Flanders]], [[Wallonia]] and the [[Brussels-Capital Region]]. SNCV/NMVB was broken up in 1991 into [[De Lijn]] (for Flanders) and [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 R\u00e9gionale Wallonne du Transport|TEC]] (for Wallonia), both companies were now primarily operating buses. De Lijn inherited the tram systems in [[Ghent]] and [[Antwerp]] (including the [[Antwerp Pre-metro|Pre-metro]]), operated previously by local companies MIVG and MIVA respectively, and the coastal tramway. TEC operates the [[Charleroi Pre-metro]], which includes sections of Vicinal track. [[STIB/MIVB]] operates the {{Track gauge|1435mm|allk=on}} [[Brussels Metro]], [[Trams in Brussels|tram]] and [[Brussels buses|bus]] network.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SNCV Signal Arr\u00eat du Train.jpg|Train signal\nFile:Tramparade 4 Benzinetram.jpg|\"Tramparade 125 years of vicinal railways\", 4th tram of the parade\nFile:Museumterrein Schepdaal 3.JPG|{{Interlanguage link multi|Trammuseum van Schepdaal|nl}}\nFile:Tourinnes bew.jpg|Steam tram in {{Interlanguage link multi|Tourinnes-Saint-Lambert|fr}}\nFile:Alle SNCV 9.jpg|[[Vresse-sur-Semois|Alle]] [[:fr:Alle (Belgique)|(fr)]] station building, just outside village, now used as a local office for the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 R\u00e9gionale Wallonne du Transport]]\nFile:NMVB Type 3.JPG|Steam locomotive.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|SNCV/NMVB}}\n* [http://www.asvi.be/ Tramway Touristique Lobbes-Thuin]\n* [http://www.tta.be/ Tramway Touristique de l'Aisne]\n* [http://www.tramania.com/ Photo archives] of the Vicinal tramways\n* [http://www.vicinal.com Vicinal tram history and preservation activities]\n* [http://trambelgium.atspace.com/index.htm Trambelgium] (with NMVB/SNCV history)\n* [http://en.sporvognsrejser.dk/byer/buurtspoorwegen_chemins_vicinaux_nmvb_sncv Tram Travels: Vicinal tramway (NMVB/SNCV)]\n* {{PM20|FID=co/067434|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Transport in Belgium}}\n\n[[Category:Tram transport in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Interurban railways]]\n[[Category:Metre gauge railways in Belgium]]\n[[Category:3 ft 6 in gauge railways in Belgium]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Tramways vicinaux''' or '''Buurtspoorwegen''' were a system of [[narrow-gauge]] [[light rail|tramway]]s or local [[railway]]s in [[Belgium]], which covered the whole country and had a greater route length than the mainline railway system. They were {{RailGauge|1000mm}} gauge ([[metre gauge]]) and included electrified city lines and rural lines using [[steam locomotive]]s and [[Diesel engine|diesel]] railcars; half the system was electrified.\n\nThe company gradually switched to buses and dismantled the tram tracks. Only the [[Belgian coast tram|coastal line]], the [[Charleroi]] metro and the short line to the caves at [[Han-sur-Lesse]] are still in commercial use; four museums hold significant collections of rolling stock, including the museum at [[Schepdaal]] and the [[ASVi museum]] in [[Thuin]].\n\nThe longest ({{convert|11|km|abbr=on}}) and oldest (40 years) [[tourist tramway]] is the ''[[Tramway Touristique de l'Aisne]]'', or 'TTA', between [[Erez\u00e9e]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Dochamps|fr}}. A sponsoring group called 'Tramania' has supported various tramway preservation initiatives for 13 years, in particular financing construction of the Thuin museum and car restoration for TTA.\n\n==NMVB / SNCV==\nLegislation allowing the construction of rural tramways was passed in 1875, followed by a new law in 1885. The result was the creation of the national Vicinal tramway company \u2013 ''Nationale Maatschappij van Buurtspoorwegen (NMVB)'' in [[Dutch language|Dutch]], ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 nationale des chemins de fer vicinaux (SNCV)'' in [[French language|French]]. The majority of lines were {{Track gauge|1000mm|allk=on}}, although until 1921 many in the Antwerp area were {{Track gauge|1067mm|lk=on}} gauge, later [[Track gauge conversion|re-gauged]]. Many lines were built alongside roads, and carried considerable quantities of freight (especially timber and agricultural produce) as well as passengers.\n\n[[World War I]] and [[World War II]] saw greatly increased traffic despite some wartime damage. The non-electric network reached a peak of approximately {{convert|3,938|km}} in 1925, but soon parts started to close